Well Evaluation
Marathon Oil Company
Force 44-20TFH
Figure 1. H&P rig #438 drilling the Marathon Oil Company,
Force 44-20TFH in Dunn County, North Dakota in October of 2014.
INTRODUCTION
The Marathon Oil Company, Force 44-20TFH [SW SE Section 20, T146N, R93W; 325' FSL,
1,350' FEL] is to be drilled by Helmerich and Payne rig #438 and is located approximately 6.5
miles northeast of the town of Dunn Center in Dunn County, North Dakota (Figure 1). The
Force 44-20TFH will be a dual section well, with an approximately 10,000' long lateral designed
to further oil production in the area. The surface will be drilled using fresh water drilling fluid,
while the vertical and curve sections will use diesel invert drilling fluid. Well plans called for
the vertical section to be drilled to a kick off point of 10,152' measured depth (MD). The curve
would then be built at a rate of 12.00º/100' and would land in the middle of the Three Forks
Formation, target interval set by the Marathon Oil Company geologist. After casing the vertical
and curve, the lateral will be drilled using a salt-water drilling fluid. Geo-steering and
directional drilling techniques will be used to maintain maximum exposure to the target zone.
The planned lateral section was to be drilled northeast, at an azimuth of 5.05º. Upon anticipated
completion of the Force 44-20TFH, the hole will be prepared for casing and production
evaluation. The hole will be lined and will use a 30 stage artificial fracture technique to
maximize the production value.
OFFSET WELLS
Three offset wells were used as primary controls while drilling the Force 44-20TFH. Data
including gamma-ray signatures, from nearby offset wells were used to determine a prognosis of
formation tops. These wells include:
The Lucy Fleckenstein 34-20H [SW SE Section 20, T146N, R93W] which is located
56' SE, on the same pad as Force 44-20TFH. This well was drilled by Marathon Oil
Company in January of 2011. It is a lateral, Middle Bakken well and is a dry well.
The Greider 34-20TFH [NW NE Section 29, T146N, R93W] which is located
approximately 0.25 miles SE from Force 44-20TFH. This well was drilled by
Marathon Oil Company in September of 2014. It is a lateral, Three Forks well and is
currently awaiting completion.
The VMR Trust 11-16TFH [SW SW Section 9, T146N, R93W] which is located
approximately 2.2 miles N-NE from Force 44-20TFH. This well was drilled by
Marathon Oil Company in September of 2014. It is a lateral, Three Forks well and is
currently awaiting completion.
The vicinity of these wells to the subject wells surface location made them ideal for developing a
well-rounded prognosis of formation tops. These three offsets were also used for structure
control during the lateral (Figure 2).
Figure 2. A map showing offset wells in relation to the Force 44-20TFH (NDIC, 2014).
ENGINEERING
The Force 44-20TFH was spud on October 11, 2014 by H&P's rig #438. The surface hole was
drilled using a 12 ¼" PDC bit and 5" drill pipe to a depth of 2,128' MD, in 4.2 drilling hours. A
freshwater based drilling fluid was used during this operation. The surface hole was then
isolated using 52 joints of 9 " J55 casing set to 2,113' MD and cemented to surface before
beginning the remaining vertical hole. The remaining vertical hole was started on October 13,
2014. Freshwater was displaced by invert diesel drilling fluid with mud weights fluctuating
between 9.60-10.10 pounds per gallon. Using two 8 ¾" PDC Security bits the vertical hole was
truly maintained at approximately 3.0º to the southeast using multiple magnetic slides to reach a
kick-off point (KOP) of 10,164' MD, in a combined 54.4 drilling hours. The curve build began
on October 17, 2014. A new bottom-hole assembly (BHA) was built including an 8 ¾" PDC
Smith bit, 2.38° fixed motor, and an MWD tool. The curve was drilled to a total depth of
10,915' MD, in 8.5 drilling hours. 7" casing was then set to 10,898' MD using 125 joints of
L80 set to 5,855' MD and 110 joints of P110 set from 5,855' to 10,898' MD. The casing was
then cemented prior to beginning the lateral section. Diesel invert drilling fluid was displaced
with a salt water based drilling fluid before beginning the lateral on October 20, 2014. Mud
weights were typically in the range of 9.70-10.0 pounds per gallon. A 6" PDC Smith bit was
used along with a 1.40° fixed mud motor and an MWD tool. A trip was necessary at 19,398'
MD due to low penetration rates. A new BHA was built including a new PDC Security bit, a new
mud motor and a new MWD tool. This assembly was drilled to total depth in a combined 64.9
drilling hours. The Force 44-20TFH reached a total depth of 20,893' MD on October 25, 2014,
at a closure direction of 5.06° and a true vertical depth (TVD) of 10,646.16'. The bottom-hole
location is: 10,034.05' north and 889.08' east of the surface location or approximately 216.35'
FNL and 460.92' FEL, NE NE Section 17, T146N, R93W (Figure 3).

GEOLOGIC EVALUATION
Methods
Geologic analysis for the Force 44-20TFH was provided by two Sunburst Consulting well-site
geologists. Gas levels were monitored using a digital gas detector and chromatograph. The
chromatograph was interfaced with a Pason electronic data recorder. The Pason relayed data
such as measured depth, bit depth, and pump stroke information to the MController gas
monitoring software. MController returned gas in the form of total gas units (100 units = 1%
methane equivalent in air) to be logged and displayed across the drilling location. Multiple
component gases (ethane, methane, propane, and butane) and their concentrations were recorded
in parts per million. ¼" Poly-Flo ® tubing was used to direct gas into the chromatograph where
the data was then translated and lagged to the correct depth. Rig crews caught lagged samples,
in 30' intervals, under the supervision of well-site geologists. Analysis and evaluation of gas and
drill cuttings began in the Kibbey Formation at 8,200' MD and ended in the Three Forks
Formation at 20,893'. Cuttings were observed in wet (isopropyl alcohol) and dry conditions
under a binocular microscope.
Lithology
At the request of Marathon Oil Company, logging began approximately 50-100' above the
prognosis top of the Kibbey "Lime", an interval of limestone within the Kibbey Formation.
The Kibbey Formation (Mississippian, Big Snowy Group) consists of red-orange siltstone with
some gray to red interbedded silty sandstone. There is a very distinct layer of limestone within
the Kibbey, referred to as the "Kibbey Lime", which was logged at 8,286' TVD (-5,954' MSL)
and consists of light to medium gray mudstone. There is a thin layer of anhydrite right above the
limestone that marks the top of the "Kibbey Lime" marker.
The Charles Formation (Mississippian, Madison Group) consists of limestone and a large
amount of evaporates including salt and anhydrite. The Charles First Salt was logged at 8,433'
TVD (-6,101' MSL), marking the top of the formation. The prospective Ratcliffe interval is
located below the Charles First Salt marker and was logged at 8,841' TVD (-6,509' MSL).
The Mission Canyon Formation (Mississippian, Madison Group) consists of gray to brown
limestone and was logged at 9,099' TVD (-6,767' MSL). Some areas contain algae laminations,
fossil fragments, and trace amounts of intercrystalline porosity and dead oil stain.
The Lodgepole Formation (Mississippian, Madison Group) is characterized by light to medium
gray argillaceous limestone. The top was logged at 9,649' TVD (-7,317' MSL) and is marked by
a transition from limestone to argillaceous limestone. The "False Bakken" is a layer of shale
near the bottom of the Lodgepole Formation. It was logged at 10,500' TVD (-8,168' MSL). The
"Scallion" is a layer of limestone at the base of the Lodgepole Formation. It was logged at
10,510' TVD (-8,178' MSL). Several other Lodgepole markers were also used to determine if a
change to the landing target was necessary.
The Bakken Formation (Mississippian-Devonian) is comprised of two layers of black,
petroliferous shale and a mixed clastic and carbonate middle and lower member. The Upper
Bakken Shale Member was logged at 10,522' TVD (-8,190' MSL). This member is recognized
by its high gamma counts, increase in rate of penetration (ROP), and typically higher total gas
units (Figure 4). The Middle Bakken Member consists of three distinct lithologies and was
logged at 10,539' TVD (-8,207' MSL). A layer of siltstone lies directly below the upper
member. Below the siltstone lies a laterally discontinuous layer of fossiliferous (packstone)
limestone. Below the limestone is a gray to brown silty sandstone (Figure 5). The Lower
Bakken Shale Member was logged at 10,575' TVD (-8,243' MSL). This member is very similar
to the upper shale but it is distinguished by a slightly darker sheen (Figure 6). The Pronghorn
Member was logged at 10,590' TVD (-8,258' MSL) and consists of a varying lithology
sequence, including siltstone, shale and dolomite.
Figure 4, 5, & 6. Wet cuttings of upper Bakken shale (left), middle Bakken silty sandstone (middle) & lower
Bakken shale (right, 10x magnification).
The Three Forks Formation (Devonian) consists of off white to tan, microcrystalline dolomite
as well as lenses of pale blue to pale blue-gray shale. It is characterized by a gamma signature
ranging from 50-140 (API) and was logged at 10,599' TVD (-8,267' MSL). The dolomite
contains trace amounts of intercrystalline porosity and spotty oil staining. The shale is pale blue
to gray-blue and contains trace amounts of oil stain in some areas (Figure 7).
Figure 7. Wet cuttings of sandy dolomite and pale blue shale in the Three Forks target zone at 30x.
Geo-steering
The well prognosis called for a landing target of 10,623' TVD at an inclination of 90°. The
landing target was set 40' below the base of the lower Bakken shale and 5' below the top of the
target area. Using gamma-ray data, well-site geologists were able to correlate formation tops
from the Force 44-20TFH to nearby offset wells in the area to assure an accurate landing. After
logging the False Bakken top, the decision was made to drop the landing target 2' to 10,625'
TVD. The decision was based on the tops coming in consistently low to the prognosis and the
nearby Lucy Fleckenstein 34-20H well. Due to a hard layer of pyritic sandstone high in the
upper Three Forks, the location of the landing target was meant to avoid any potentially
hazardous drilling while remaining in a productive area of the Three Forks. The actual curve
landing came in at 10,621' TVD, landing the well-bore 3' into the 10' target area.
The target zone top is marked by a cool gamma trough and off white, tan, and gray dolomite with
lenses of pale blue to pale blue gray shale in sample. Gamma-ray readings varied from 60-120
(API) counts while in target. The location of the target area put the top of the target 28' below
the base of the lower Bakken shale and the base of the target 9' above the top of the chocolate
dolomite.
The Three Forks target zone was entered at approximately 10,873' MD (10,618' TVD). The
well-bore was maintained in the target zone for 87% of the lateral. The formation dropped 19.80'
of TVD, over the course of the lateral, with a gross dip of -0.11° (Figure 8).

Gas and Oil Show
The label used to quantify gas for this well was units (100 units is equal to 1% methane
equivalent in air). The first time any significant gas was logged was a gas show while drilling of
23 units in the Charles Formation. There were multiple gas shows from 11-43 units logged
during vertical drilling. Gas increased substantially in the "Scallion", and included a trip gas
show of of 2,771 units while circulating after the curve landing. There were multiple gas shows
around 100-1,700 units from the False Bakken to the curve landing, likely due to fracture
porosity.
Background gas in the lateral ranged from 100 to 1,800 units. Throughout parts of the lateral
there were higher concentrations of background gas and gas shows, specifically from 12,944'-
14,574' MD possibly due to a high location in zone and/or crossing of fracture porosity. Trace
to ocassional amounts of tan-yellow oil were observed over the shakers and was occasionally
observed in the sample wash. The highest gas show in the lateral was a trip gas show of 5,312
units and was logged while circulating at 19,398' MD. Gas was vented through the gas buster
from 10,915'-14,570' MD. Gas was circulated through the gas buster from 14,570'-20,893'
(TD) and a 1-3' intermittent flare was observed. A 5-20' trip flare was observed while
circulating at 19,398' MD. No back pressure was held at anytime during the lateral (Figure 9).

SUMMARY
The Marathon Oil Company, Force 44-20TFH is a Three Forks lateral well located northeast of
the town of Dunn Center in Dunn County, North Dakota. It was spud on October 11, 2014 and
was drilled to a kick off point of 10,164' MD. The curve was landed at 10,621' TVD, 3' into the
target zone. Dolomite in the target interval contained intercrystalline porosity and trace to rare
amounts of light brown oil staining. Background gas in the lateral ranged from 100-1,800 units,
with gas shows as high as 5,312 units. Throughout parts of the lateral there were trace to
occasional amounts of yellow-tan oil over the shakers and trace amounts of oil in the sample
wash. The well-bore was maintained within the target interval for 87% of 10,020' lateral
section. The Force 44-20TFH reached a total depth of 20,893' MD on October 25, 2014 after 15
drilling days.
Respectfully Submitted,
Nicholas R. Higgins
Sunburst Consulting, Inc.

LITHOLOGY
Rig crews caught lagged samples in 30' intervals under the supervision of Sunburst geologists. A detailed list of
sampling intervals is included in the well data summary page. Sample or gamma-ray marker tops have been
inserted in the sample descriptions below for reference. Samples were examined wet and dry under a binocular
microscope. The drilling fluid was diesel-based invert from surface casing to 10,915' MD, and changed to salt
water from 10,915' to 20,893' (TD). Sample collection began at 8,200' MD.
Drilling in the Kibbey Formation [Big Snowy Group]
8200-8230 SILTSTONE: red-brown to orange-brown, soft to friable, blocky, calcite cemented, poorly cemented,
sandy in part; common SILTY SANDSTONE: off white to light gray tan, fine grained, friable, sub-rounded, calcite
cemented, moderately to well cemented
8230-8260 SILTSTONE: red-brown to orange-brown, soft to friable, blocky, calcite cemented, poorly cemented,
sandy in part; occasional SILTY SANDSTONE: off white to light gray, occasional light gray tan, fine grained,
friable, sub-rounded, calcite cemented, moderately to well cemented
8260-8290 SILTSTONE: red-brown to orange-brown, soft to friable, blocky, calcite cemented, poorly cemented,
sandy in part; trace SILTY SANDSTONE: off white to light gray, occasional tan, fine grained, friable, sub-rounded,
calcite cemented, moderately to well cemented

Well File # 29442
Dear Natalie:
Pursuant to Commission Order No. 24818, approval to drill the above captioned well is hereby given. The
approval is granted on the condition that all portions of the well bore not isolated by cement, be no closer than the 200'
setback from the north & south boundaries, 440' setback boundary from the east and 500' setback from the west
boundary within the 1280 acre spacing unit consisting of Sections 20 & 17 T146N R93W. Tool error is not required
pursuant to order.
PERMIT STIPULATIONS: The horizontal well located approximately 440 feet from the west boundary
in the standup 1280-acre spacing unit described as Sections 16 and 21, Township 146 North, Range 93
West, Dunn County, North Dakota, in Zone V in the Bailey-Bakken Pool; and the horizontal well
located approximately 440 feet from the east boundary in the standup 1280-acre spacing unit described
as Sections 17 and 20, Township 146 North, Range 93 West, Dunn County, North Dakota, in Zone VI in
the Bailey-Bakken Pool, shall be permitted simultaneously and drilled and completed at approximately
the same time. Effective June 1, 2014, a covered leak-proof container (with placard) for filter sock
disposal must be maintained on the well site beginning when the well is spud, and must remain on-site
during clean-out, completion, and flow-back whenever filtration operations are conducted.
MARATHON OIL COMPANY must take into consideration NDAC 43-02-03-28 (Safety Regulation)
when contemplating simultaneous operations on the above captioned location. Pursuant to NDAC 43-
02-03-28 (Safety Regulation) "No boiler, portable electric lighting generator, or treater shall be placed
nearer than 150 feet to any producing well or oil tank." MARATHON OIL CO must contact NDIC Field
Inspector Ashleigh Devenberg at 701-290-3277prior to location construction.
Drilling pit
NDAC 43-02-03-19.4 states that "a pit may be utilized to bury drill cuttings and solids generated during well drilling
and completion operations, providing the pit can be constructed, used and reclaimed in a manner that will prevent
pollution of the land surface and freshwaters. Reserve and circulation of mud system through earthen pits are
prohibited. All pits shall be inspected by an authorized representative of the director prior to lining and use. Drill
cuttings and solids must be stabilized in a manner approved by the director prior to placement in a cuttings pit."
Form 1 Changes & Hard Lines
Any changes, shortening of casing point or lengthening at Total Depth must have prior approval by the NDIC. The
proposed directional plan is at a legal location. Based on the azimuth of the proposed lateral the maximum legal
coordinate from the well head is: 10050 N & 910 E.
Natalie Menge
September 17, 2014
Page 2
Location Construction Commencement (Three Day Waiting Period)
Operators shall not commence operations on a drill site until the 3rd business day following publication of the
approved drilling permit on the NDIC - OGD Daily Activity Report. If circumstances require operations to
commence before the 3rd business day following publication on the Daily Activity Report, the waiting period may be
waived by the Director. Application for a waiver must be by sworn affidavit providing the information necessary to
evaluate the extenuating circumstances, the factors of NDAC 43-02-03-16.2 (1), (a)-(f), and any other information that
would allow the Director to conclude that in the event another owner seeks revocation of the drilling permit, the
applicant should retain the permit.
Permit Fee & Notification
Payment was received in the amount of $100 via credit card. It is requested that notification be given
immediately upon the spudding of the well. This information should be relayed to the Oil & Gas Division, Bismarck,
via telephone. The following information must be included: Well name, legal location, permit number, drilling
contractor, company representative, date and time of spudding. Office hours are 8:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. and 1:00 p.m.
to 5:00 p.m. Central Time. Our telephone number is (701) 328-8020, leave a message if after hours or on the weekend.
Survey Requirements for Horizontal, Horizontal Re-entry, and Directional Wells
NDAC Section 43-02-03-25 (Deviation Tests and Directional Surveys) states in part (that) the survey contractor
shall file a certified copy of all surveys with the director free of charge within thirty days of completion. Surveys must
be submitted as one electronic copy, or in a form approved by the director. However, the director may require the
directional survey to be filed immediately after completion if the survey is needed to conduct the operation of the
director's office in a timely manner. Certified surveys must be submitted via email in one adobe document, with a
certification cover page to certsurvey@nd.gov.
Survey points shall be of such frequency to accurately determine the entire location of the well bore.
Specifically, the Horizontal and Directional well survey frequency is 100 feet in the vertical, 30 feet in the curve (or
when sliding) and 90 feet in the lateral.
Confidential status
Your request for confidential status of all information furnished to the Director, or his representatives, is hereby
granted. Such information, except production runs, shall remain confidential for six months commencing on the date
the well is spud.
Confidential status notwithstanding, the Director and his representatives shall have access to all well records
wherever located. Your company personnel, or any person performing work for your company shall permit the
Director and his representatives to come upon any lease, property, well, or drilling rig operated or controlled by them,
complying with all safety rules, and to inspect the records and operation of such wells and to have access at all times to
any and all records of wells. The Commission's field personnel periodically inspect producing and drilling wells. Any
information regarding such wells shall be made available to them at any time upon request. The information so
obtained by the field personnel shall be maintained in strict confidence and shall be available only to the Commission
and its staff.
Surface casing cement
Tail cement utilized on surface casing must have a minimum compressive strength of 500 psi within 12 hours,
and tail cement utilized on production casing must have a minimum compressive strength of 500 psi before drilling the
plug or initiating tests.
Logs
NDAC Section 43-02-03-31 requires the running of (1) a suite of open hole logs from which formation tops and
porosity zones can be determined, (2) a Gamma Ray Log run from total depth to ground level elevation of the well
bore, and (3) a log from which the presence and quality of cement can be determined (Standard CBL or Ultrasonic
cement evaluation log) in every well in which production or intermediate casing has been set, this log must be run prior
to completing the well. All logs run must be submitted free of charge, as one digital TIFF (tagged image file format)
copy and one digital LAS (log ASCII) formatted copy. Digital logs may be submitted on a standard CD, DVD, or
attached to an email sent to digitallogs@nd.gov Thank you for your cooperation.

April 9, 2014
RE: Filter Socks and Other Filter Media
Leakproof Container Required
Oil and Gas Wells
Dear Operator,
North Dakota Administrative Code Section 43-02-03-19.2 states in part that all waste material associated with
exploration or production of oil and gas must be properly disposed of in an authorized facility in accord with all
applicable local, state, and federal laws and regulations.
Filtration systems are commonly used during oil and gas operations in North Dakota. The Commission is very
concerned about the proper disposal of used filters (including filter socks) used by the oil and gas industry.
Effective June 1, 2014, a container must be maintained on each well drilled in North Dakota beginning when the
well is spud and must remain on-site during clean-out, completion, and flow-back whenever filtration operations
are conducted. The on-site container must be used to store filters until they can be properly disposed of in an
authorized facility. Such containers must be:
leakproof to prevent any fluids from escaping the container
covered to prevent precipitation from entering the container
placard to indicate only filters are to be placed in the container
If the operator will not utilize a filtration system, a waiver to the container requirement will be considered, but
only upon the operator submitting a Sundry Notice (Form 4) justifying their request.
As previously stated in our March 13, 2014 letter, North Dakota Administrative Code Section 33-20-02.1-01
states in part that every person who transports solid waste (which includes oil and gas exploration and production
wastes) is required to have a valid permit issued by the North Dakota Department of Health, Division of Waste
Management. Please contact the Division of Waste Management at (701) 328-5166 with any questions on the
solid waste program. Note oil and gas exploration and production wastes include produced water, drilling mud,
invert mud, tank bottom sediment, pipe scale, filters, and fly ash.
Thank you for your cooperation.
Sincerely,
Bruce E. Hicks
Assistant Director
Marathon Oil Company

1.
BOP EQUIPMENT
Marathon Oil Company's minimum specifications for pressure
control equipment are as follows:
Ram Type:
13 5/8" 5000 psi blind, pipe and annular.
a. Due to Marathon's experience it is felt that the above
referenced BOP equipment is adequate for drilling this well.
The reduced permeability of the target zone along with
Marathon's area experience of drilling over 250 horizontal
wells indicate that a MASP of 3000 psi is more adjusted to
the reality of the reservoir.
BOP and other equipment testing:
a. Floor valve, dart valve, kill valves, check valve, manual
choke line valve, manual top drive valve, hydraulic top
drive valve, HCR, choke house valves, choke manifold,
choke hose, choke line, kill line, upper pipe rams, lower
pipe rams, blind rams (Low Test: 250 psi x 5 min. High
Test: 5000 psi x 10 min.)
b. Annular Preventer (Low Test: 250 psi x 5 min. High Test:
2500 psi x 10 min.)
c. Rotating head and Orbit Valve (Low Test: 250 psi x 5 min.
High Test: 1500 psi x 10 min.)
Frequency:
a. After initial installation (NU BOPE).
b. Whenever any seal subject to test pressure is broken.
c. After any repairs compromising seal.
d. At 30-day intervals.
All other equipment (upper and lower Kelly cocks, IBOP,
etc) will be tested according to Onshore Oil and Gas
Order No. 2.

ABNORMAL PRESSURES AND H2S GAS
a. The maximum anticipated bottom-hole pressure is 7810 psi.
Abnormal pressures are not anticipated.

6.
Well Completion
a. A 4 ½" liner will be run from above the 7" casing shoe to
the bottom of the well.
Liner has frac sleeves
installed.
b. Tie back liner will be run from top of 4 ½" Liner back to
the surface.
c. Well will be fractured utilizing a 30 stage frac.
d. Pursuant to NDIC letter effective February 12,2014,
concerning Hydraulic Fracture Stimulation using Diesel
Fuels, Marathon Oil Company will not inject diesel fuel
or any diesel-type chemicals (68334-30-5, 68476-34-6,
68476-30-2, 68476-31-3, or 8008-20-6) during the
hydraulic fracture stimulation process or this well.
Marathon understands the guidelines that are outline in
the above referenced letter including the requirement to
obtain an Underground Injection Control, Class II permit
from the NDIC prior to commencing any Hydraulic Fracture
Stimulation in which any amount of diesel fuel or any
diesel type chemical is injected.

Field: Bailey
Flowback Strategy
Anticipated First Production date
The Force 44-20TFH is expected to commence production around December 2014. It is anticipated that it will be
connected to a gas sales pipeline at first production.
Multi-well startup
The well is expected to flowback concurrently the re-frac'ed Lucy Fleckenstein 34-20H. Flowback of the well is
expected to be approximately 4-10 days in duration.
Anticipated Oil and Gas Rates
Average rates contributed rom the Lucy Fleckenstein pad (Force and Lucy Fleckenstein wells) during flowback:
-
Average gas rate for the pad is anticipated to be: 800 MSCFD
-
Average oil rate for the pad is anticipated to be: 1,200 BOPD
Average rates the Krebs pad (total of all 7 wells), during the Force and Lucy Fleckenstein flowback (other 5 wells
having previously flowed back):
-
Average gas rate for the pad is anticipated to be: 2,200 MSCFD
-
Average oil rate for the pad is anticipated to be: 3,100 BOPD
